FAA: The air passengers can from now on use gadgets on board planes (but not to pass a call with their mobile phone)
The passengers of the airline companies will be able to use their electronic devices of door with door for reading, working, to play games, to look at films and to listen to music – but not to speak on their mobile phone – under the terms of the new very expected directives published Thursday by Federal Aviation Administration.
But the passengers should not expect immediate changes.
The speed with which the change will be set up will vary from one airline company to another, declared the administrator of the FAA Michael Huerta at the time of a press conference.
The airline companies will have to prove with the FAA that theirs planes respect the new directives and that they updated the training manuals of the team members and the rules concerning the storage of the devices to be in conformity.
The FAA declared that it had already received plans of certain airline companies aiming at widening the use of the electronic devices on theirs planes.
Delta and JetBlue are part of the companies which already subjected plans.
“According to the plan, we could approve a widened use of the electronic devices very soon”, the FAA in a declaration indicated.
Currently, the passengers must extinguish their smartphones, shelves and other devices as soon as the doors of the plane are closed.
They are not supposed to relight them before the plane reaches an altitude of 10 000 feet and that the commander gives his green light.
The passengers are supposed to extinguish their devices at the time of the descent of the plane before the landing and not to relight them until the plane landed.
Under the terms of the new directives, the airline companies whose planes are correctly protected from the electronic interferences will be able to authorize the passengers to use their devices during takeoffs, the landings and the bearing on the ground, declared the FAA.
Most new airliners and other planes which were modified so that the passengers can use Wi-Fi at more raised altitudes, should satisfy the criteria.
Laura Glading, president of Association of Professional Flight Waiting, is known as happy of these changes.
“Once the new policy put in work in full safety – and we will work in close collaboration with the carriers for that – it will be advantageous with everyone”, explained Glading in a declaration.
We are frankly tired to feel us as “head nurses” when it is about this question.
But it will be always interdict to connect itself to Internet for surfing, to exchange e-mails and of SMS or to download data below 10 000 feet, declared the agency.
The passengers will have to put their smartphones, shelves and other devices in plane mode.
Thus still not of Words With Friends, the online game style Scrabble which the actor Alec Baldwin played on his smartphone in 2011 when it was expelled with great noise of a plane of American Airlines after having refused to extinguish his device whereas the device was parked with the door.
And the devices heavier as the laptops will have to always be arranged because they could wound somebody if they flew through the cabin.
The mobile phones on board will also continue to be prohibited.
The lawful power concerning the mobile phones belongs to Federal the Communications Commission and not to the FAA.
The FAA can raise prohibition on certain electronic devices during takeoff and the landing
Last month, Mark Rosenker of the National Transportation Safety Board, national expert in transport safety on CBS News, declared that the mobile phones were always regarded as presenting a risk.
“The mobile phones are truly a problem, not only because they could possibly create interferences with the instruments of navigation, but because we know, according to the FCC, that they could disturb the antenna-relays of mobile telephony if they are used on board”, Rosenker declared.
An industrial advisory committee created by the FAA to examine the problem recommended last month that the government authorizes a broader use of the personal electronic devices.
The pressure weighing on the FAA was reinforced during last years to soften the restrictions relating to their use.
Detractors such as the sénatrice Claire McCaskill, D-Mo., support that there does not exist any safety reason valid for these prohibitions.
The restrictions are also increasingly difficult to apply because the use of the devices became omnipresent.
Certain studies indicate that at least a third of the passengers forgets to extinguish their devices, or do it deliberately.
The FAA started to limit the use of the electronic devices in 1996 following the reports on the presence of interferences with the instruments of navigation and communication when the passengers transported FM radios, the gadget high-tech of then.
The new airliners depend much more of the electric systems that former generations of planes, but they are also conceived to resist the electronic interferences and are approved by the FAA.
The airline companies have allowed their passengers to use Wi-Fi with altitudes of cruising for several years.
The planes modified to accommodate Wi-Fi systems resist the interferences also better.
The vast majority of the airliners should allow a broader use of the electronic devices under the terms of the new directives, declared Huerta.
The electronic devices of today in general emit radio transmissions of power much lower than the former generations of devices.
The readers of e-books, for example, emit only minimal transmissions when a page is turned.
But the transmissions are stronger when the devices download or send data.
Amazon.com is part of those which put pressure for an easing of the restrictions concerning the use of the electronic devices by the passengers.
In 2011, the officers of the company charged an airliner with readers of e-books Kindle and made it fly to see whether there were problems, but there was none of it.
That inspired to the members of the advisory committee of the FAA of the mixed feelings as for the question of knowing if the use of the devices presents or not a risk.
Douglas Kidd of the National Association of Airline Passengers declared that he thought that the interferences coming from the devices were real, even if the risk were tiny.
Other members of the committee declared that there exist only anecdotic reports emanating from pilots who indicate that the devices can interfere with the systems of a plane, and that most between them are very old.
However, the committee recommended that the FAA authorizes the pilots to be requested from the passengers to extinguish their devices during the instrument landings under conditions of low visibility.
A group of the industry of the travel was pleased with the changes, calling them of arrangements full with good sense for travellers equipped with technologies.
“We are happy that the FAA recognizes that an experiment pleasant passenger is not incompatible with the security”, Roger Dow, President and director of the U.S. Travel Association declared.
