How biometrics will invade our lives
Finished the passwords to be typed to reach its smartphone or to pay its purchases?
The American, French researchers or Japanese predict a future to us where we will be recognized by the biometric sensors of the telephones and the computers.
Bernard Didier, executive vice president of Morpho, even estimates that “the century will be biometric”.
Only biometrics will make it possible to make sure of the identity of a person realizing of the transactions in a as transverse and transnational universe as Internet.
The organizations dedicated to protection of privacy confirm this passion for biometrics, but worry some.
Only in 2011 and in France, the National Commission of data processing and freedoms authorized 774 systems of recognition of the prints, of the form of the hand or the venous network of the hand in companies, administrations, canteens…
“Everyone could be identified soon, anywhere and any time”, is moved Justin Brookman, person in charge of the private life of the consumers within the CDT (Center for Democracy and Technology), in Washington.
Reasons of such an optimism, at the ones, and pessimism, at the others?
Biometrics will be based on novel methods, which will make it possible to do new favours for the citizens and to the consumers.
Today, in France, the most used biometric data are the digital fingerprints, the contour of the hand and the venous network of the palm or the fingers.
But each one of these techniques has its constraints.
“For example, certain people who work the concrete have the very damaged fingers and their prints are illegible”, Philippe Robin, works manager of the identity field in Thales Communications & Security notes.
And the collection as well as the checking of the venous network and the contour of the hand suppose a voluntary and precise gesture people.
It is at the same time a security - one cannot collect these data without their knowledge - and a disadvantage: the procedure must sometimes be repeated and thus takes time.
Consequence, of research have been carried out for about twenty years on other approaches, like the recognition of the face or the iris (the coloured part of the eye).
Thanks to the increase in the precision of the sensors and of capacity of calculation of the computers necessary to the data analysis, these techniques become operational.
The precision of the facial recognition was multiplied by ten during five last years, calculates Cyrille Bataller, director of the laboratories of R & D of Accenture in Europe.
With our assistance, the United Kingdom and Holland deployed automatic border posts using the facial recognition.
It is from now on possible to identify a face or an iris moving.
“Today, we undertake researches on the recognition of the voice or the way of walking using sound sensors, but one needs a quiet environment”, indicates Sridhar Iyengar, director of research on the security in Intel Labs.
Single and unfalsifiable marker, the DNA also raises hopes and concerns.
“In the actual position of knowledge, it can be regarded as the ultimate biometric data”, confirms Sophie Vulliet-Tavernier, director of the studies, the innovation and the futurology with the CNIL.
But the analysis of the DNA is still very long and very expensive.
NEC proposes at the police services legal a bag costing 90,000 euros to analyze samples of DNA on the place of a crime and in one hour.
The uses of biometrics are divided into two groups: identification (to recognize a person among others) and authentification (to make sure that the person is that which she claims to be).
The identification related to until now the identity papers delivery: it is necessary to confront the biometric elements (impressed, photograph, iris) with information which the State has on all the already driven citizens.
That makes it possible to make sure that a person does not try to usurp the identity of someone else.
This principle of comparison can have other applications.
NEC thus proposes the recognition of VIP at the entrance of a hotel or a store.
“We recover the images of the surveillance cameras and let us compare them with the photographs celebrities who circulate freely on Internet”, explains Dany Nassif, charged, at NEC France, of the commercial development for the solutions of biometric identification.
Another use: to take in photograph a fellow which makes the tail in a store, to follow its progression thanks to the facial recognition and to calculate the latency.
The authentification related to at the beginning the physical accesses (protected borders, buildings, canteens…) or logics (opening of a computer).
Was added there, more recently, the control of presence.
“Pointer biometric avoids the phenomenon of the buddy who points for another”, Cyrille Bataller justifies, from Accenture.
But, more and more, the authentification will also relate to the transactions, in particular those carried out starting from devices connected to Internet.
In Japan, it is already possible to withdraw money with certain distributors by introducing its map and by posing its hand on a biometric reader: this gesture replaces the striking of the PIN number.
A similar technique is tested in Villeneuve-d'Ascq and Angouleme by the company Natural Security in partnership with banks and signs of large distribution: at the time to pay in store with his credit card, the customer does not type his code, but introduced his finger into a reader who scans the veins.
The experimentation is designed to last six months.
If it is conclusive, the biometric readers could arrive soon in the French tradesmen.
Tracks to reassure the users
There exist three manners of making biometrics tempting to the eyes of the general public.
First is to explain that it can make save time.
“If, thanks to biometrics, a customer remains in case thirty seconds of less, it is appreciable”, explains the director of a large surface.
Second is to offer personalized services: in a few years, a vocal waiter will be able to recognize your voice and to propose custom-tailored options to you.
And, finally, to reassure by proposing the precautions taken to protect the databases.
“The digital fingerprints are stored on a first waiter; the identities of the people are in one second base: the correlation between the two numbers is encrypted and stored in a highly secure case, which is blocked if one tries to move it”, enumerates Philippe Robin, from Thales.
But, for lack of in-depth studies, it is impossible to know if these speeches convince really the users.
The specialists in protection of privacy, them, continue to worry.
“Progress of the facial recognition, the multiplication of the surveillance cameras and the enormous quantity of photographs available on Facebook, Flickr or Picasa, make me fear the worst: a generalized monitoring”, predicted Andrew Patrick, Police station with protection of privacy in Canada.
